respectfully, we love him.

222
00:14:55,936 --> 00:14:57,896
We're not about to let him go.

223
00:14:58,105 --> 00:15:00,065
You got this Venezuelan kid
coming up.

224
00:15:00,232 --> 00:15:02,567
We had him.
We moved him to Detroit.

225
00:15:03,902 --> 00:15:05,320
What else you thinking?

226
00:15:06,488 --> 00:15:08,073
Outfielders.

227
00:15:08,240 --> 00:15:10,951
- To replace Damon?
- Yeah.

228
00:15:11,118 --> 00:15:15,789
- In your price range? No disrespect.
- Enough, Mark.

229
00:15:16,832 --> 00:15:18,500
Hollins?

230
00:15:20,544 --> 00:15:23,130
- Garcia?
- No.

231
00:15:23,296 --> 00:15:25,006
Maybe Coste.

232
00:15:27,968 --> 00:15:29,511
That's it.

233
00:15:30,846 --> 00:15:34,182
- All right, tell me about Garcia.
- To replace Johnny Damon?

234
00:15:34,850 --> 00:15:37,853
- Mark, is he healthy?
- Yeah, he's healthy-ish.

235
00:15:38,019 --> 00:15:40,480
He had that back thing.

236
00:15:40,647 --> 00:15:43,400
- He'll be ready for spring ball.
- I'll tell you what.

237
00:15:43,567 --> 00:15:46,069
I can give you Guthrie
if you kick in some cash.

238
00:15:46,236 --> 00:15:47,320
- Mark Guthrie?
- Yeah.

239
00:15:47,487 --> 00:15:49,614
- How much cash?
- Two hundred K.

240
00:16:05,964 --> 00:16:07,382
Okay.

241
00:16:08,383 --> 00:16:12,220
- So Garcia's gonna be a no.
- You're kidding me, right?

242
00:16:13,138 --> 00:16:15,474
- You're kidding me.
- I'm not.

243
00:16:17,142 --> 00:16:20,395
Okay. Straight up, Garcia for Guthrie,
no kicker.

244
00:16:21,438 --> 00:16:24,065
- No kicker?
- Straight up.

245
00:16:27,402 --> 00:16:32,032
I think it's gonna be a hard no
on Garcia, but let's just keep going.

246
00:16:32,199 --> 00:16:35,410
- What else you thinking?
- What are we doing? Is this business?

247
00:16:35,577 --> 00:16:37,871
This is the way we do business
in Cleveland.

248
00:17:21,665 --> 00:17:23,083
Hey.

249
00:17:24,292 --> 00:17:26,795
- Hello.
- Who are you?

250
00:17:29,631 --> 00:17:31,633
I'm Peter Brand.

251
00:17:32,509 --> 00:17:34,261
What do you do?

252
00:17:35,637 --> 00:17:38,223
I'm special assistant
to Mark Shapiro.

253
00:17:38,390 --> 00:17:40,267
So, what do you do?

254
00:17:42,644 --> 00:17:46,106
Mostly player analysis right now.

255
00:17:46,273 --> 00:17:49,985
Been on the job long?
First job in baseball?

256
00:17:51,444 --> 00:17:53,822
It's my first job anywhere.

257
00:17:53,989 --> 00:17:56,449
- Wow, congrats.
- Thank you.

258
00:17:56,616 --> 00:17:59,244
First job. Whose nephew are you?

259
00:18:01,663 --> 00:18:03,498
Why does Mark listen to you?

260
00:18:06,126 --> 00:18:07,961
I don't think...

261
00:18:08,670 --> 00:18:11,006
I don't think he does very often.

262
00:18:12,465 --> 00:18:14,342
He just did.

263
00:18:16,428 --> 00:18:17,971
Well, in that circumstance...

264
00:18:18,138 --> 00:18:21,683
I think he was more listening
to Bruce than myself.

265
00:18:23,059 --> 00:18:24,686
Who are you?

266
00:18:27,397 --> 00:18:29,649
I'm Peter Brand.

267
00:18:32,652 --> 00:18:35,697
I don't give a rat's ass
what your name is.

268
00:18:36,406 --> 00:18:38,575
What happened in there?

269
00:18:39,701 --> 00:18:41,995
What happened in that room?

270
00:18:42,412 --> 00:18:45,123
I'm not quite sure
what you're asking me, Mr. Beane.

271
00:18:45,290 --> 00:18:47,709
What did you tell Bruce?

272
00:18:48,877 --> 00:18:53,381
- I just told Bruce I like Garcia.
- You like Garcia. Why?

273
00:18:55,675 --> 00:18:57,385
Why?

274
00:19:02,432 --> 00:19:03,975
I don't know.

275
00:19:21,576 --> 00:19:24,454
There is an epidemic failure
within the game...

276
00:19:24,621 --> 00:19:27,248
to understand
what is really happening.

277
00:19:27,415 --> 00:19:31,878
And this leads people who run
Major League Baseball teams...

278
00:19:32,045 --> 00:19:36,216
to misjudge their players
and mismanage their teams.

279
00:19:40,804 --> 00:19:42,764
I apologize.

280
00:19:43,723 --> 00:19:44,766
Go on.

281
00:19:48,019 --> 00:19:53,191
Okay. People who run ball clubs,
they think in terms of buying players.

282
00:19:53,775 --> 00:19:58,363
Your goal shouldn't be to buy players.
Your goal should be to buy wins.

283
00:19:58,530 --> 00:20:01,908
And in order to buy wins,
you need to buy runs.

284
00:20:02,075 --> 00:20:04,119
You're trying
to replace Johnny Damon.

285
00:20:04,619 --> 00:20:06,246
<i>The Red Sox see Johnny Damon...</i>

286
00:20:06,413 --> 00:20:10,083
<i>and they see a star
who's worth $7.5 million a year.</i>

287
00:20:10,250 --> 00:20:13,128
When I see Johnny Damon...

288
00:20:13,294 --> 00:20:15,630
what I see is...

289
00:20:17,048 --> 00:20:20,468
an imperfect understanding
of where runs come from.

290
00:20:21,177 --> 00:20:22,804
<i>The guy's got a great glove.</i>

291
00:20:22,971 --> 00:20:25,932
<i>He's a decent leadoff hitter.
He can steal bases.</i>

292
00:20:26,099 --> 00:20:28,476
But is he worth the $7.5 million
a year...

293
00:20:28,643 --> 00:20:30,812
that the Boston Red Sox
are paying him?

294
00:20:30,979 --> 00:20:32,814
No. No.

295
00:20:33,398 --> 00:20:35,275
<i>Baseball thinking is medieval.</i>

296
00:20:35,442 --> 00:20:37,944
<i>They are asking
all the wrong questions.</i>

297
00:20:38,111 --> 00:20:42,282
And if I say it to anybody,
I'm ostracized. I'm a leper.

298
00:20:42,449 --> 00:20:47,412
So that's why I'm cagey
about this with you.

299
00:20:47,579 --> 00:20:48,621
That's why...

300
00:20:48,788 --> 00:20:52,709
I respect you, Mr. Beane,
and if you want full disclosure...

301
00:20:53,334 --> 00:20:57,756
I think it's a good thing
that you got Damon off your payroll.

302
00:20:57,922 --> 00:21:02,469
I think it opens up all kinds
of interesting possibilities.

303
00:21:02,635 --> 00:21:05,722
- Where you from, Pete?
- Maryland.

304
00:21:05,889 --> 00:21:09,184
- Where'd you go to school?
- Yale. I went to Yale.

305
00:21:10,310 --> 00:21:13,188
- What'd you study?
- Economics.

306
00:21:13,855 --> 00:21:16,399
I studied economics.

307
00:21:19,944 --> 00:21:24,324
Yale, economics and baseball.

308
00:21:25,867 --> 00:21:28,119
You're funny, Pete.

309
00:21:51,017 --> 00:21:52,227
<i>Tell me, why Billy?</i>

310
00:21:52,977 --> 00:21:55,355
What is it that makes him special?

311
00:21:55,522 --> 00:21:59,234
Very rare do you come upon
a young man like Billy...

312
00:21:59,400 --> 00:22:02,529
who can run, who can field,
who can throw, who can hit...

313
00:22:02,695 --> 00:22:04,280
and who can hit with power.

314
00:22:04,447 --> 00:22:07,492
Those five tools,
you don't see that very often.

315
00:22:08,159 --> 00:22:11,079
Most of the youngsters
that we have an interest in...

316
00:22:11,246 --> 00:22:12,705
have one or two tools...

317
00:22:12,872 --> 00:22:15,500
and we're hoping
to develop an extra one.

318
00:22:15,667 --> 00:22:17,585
Your son has five.

319
00:22:17,752 --> 00:22:21,798
We're looking at a guy that's a
potential superstar for us in New York.

320
00:22:21,965 --> 00:22:23,842
The time is now to get him started.

321
00:22:24,008 --> 00:22:26,845
We're prepared to make
a sizable financial commitment.

322
00:22:27,011 --> 00:22:29,430
The Mets are gonna
stand behind Billy...

323
00:22:29,597 --> 00:22:32,934
because we expect him
to be our big-league center fielder.

324
00:22:33,101 --> 00:22:35,186
This check here
represents the offer...

325
00:22:35,353 --> 00:22:38,731
that the New York Mets
would be making to Billy.

326
00:22:38,898 --> 00:22:44,028
You do know that he's been accepted
to Stanford on a full scholarship?

327
00:22:44,195 --> 00:22:45,363
I do.

328
00:22:45,530 --> 00:22:47,949
So he can do both?

329
00:22:48,116 --> 00:22:52,453
Unfortunately, he can't do Stanford
and professional baseball.

330
00:22:52,620 --> 00:22:56,541
He would have to pick one
or the other.

331
00:22:56,708 --> 00:22:59,210
If he wants to be center fielder
for the Mets...

332
00:22:59,377 --> 00:23:01,254
wants to be a baseball player...

333
00:23:01,421 --> 00:23:06,301
he really needs to accept this
as life's first occupation, first career.

334
00:23:06,467 --> 00:23:10,221
We're all told at some point we can
no longer play the children's game.

335
00:23:10,388 --> 00:23:12,891
We just don't know
when that's gonna be.

336
00:23:13,391 --> 00:23:17,478
Some of us are told at 18, some of us
are told at 40, but we're all told.

337
00:23:18,104 --> 00:23:21,316
<i>But this is a once-in-a-lifetime
opportunity.</i>

338
00:23:21,482 --> 00:23:22,567
We want you badly...

339
00:23:22,734 --> 00:23:26,070
and we think that this amount
of money expresses that desire.

340
00:23:26,237 --> 00:23:29,616
Billy, this is your decision,
and whatever that decision is...

341
00:23:29,782 --> 00:23:32,285
<i>you know it's fine
with your mother and I.</i>

342
00:23:43,171 --> 00:23:45,423
<i>- Hello?</i>
- Hey, it's Billy Beane.

343
00:23:46,215 --> 00:23:50,011
- Hey, what time is it?
<i>- I don't know.</i>

344
00:23:50,970 --> 00:23:55,141
Listen, would you have drafted me
in the first round?

345
00:23:55,308 --> 00:23:56,726
<i>What?</i>

346
00:23:56,893 --> 00:24:00,438
After I left,
you looked me up on your computer.

347
00:24:00,605 --> 00:24:02,941
Would you have drafted me
in the first round?

348
00:24:03,107 --> 00:24:06,027
<i>I did, yeah.
You were a good player.</i>

349
00:24:06,194 --> 00:24:08,446
Cut the crap, man.

350
00:24:08,613 --> 00:24:11,532
Would you have drafted me
in the first round?

351
00:24:12,200 --> 00:24:16,371
<i>I'd have taken you in the ninth round.
No signing bonus.</i>

352
00:24:17,205 --> 00:24:21,709
<i>I imagine you would've passed
and taken that scholarship.</i>

353
00:24:22,377 --> 00:24:24,295
Yeah.

354
00:24:27,882 --> 00:24:30,385
<i>Pack your bags, Pete.</i>

355
00:24:30,802 --> 00:24:33,846
I just bought you
from the Cleveland Indians.

356
00:24:47,568 --> 00:24:51,072
- Is it attached to that clamp?
- Yeah, let me unhook it.

357
00:24:59,539 --> 00:25:02,083
- Slide it up right there. To the left.
- I did.

358
00:25:02,250 --> 00:25:04,419
- Yeah, yeah.
- Hang on, it's wet.

359
00:25:04,585 --> 00:25:06,170
Come on.

360
00:25:27,942 --> 00:25:29,736
- Morning, Suzanne. Coffee on?
- Yes.

361
00:25:29,902 --> 00:25:31,279
Great.

362
00:25:31,863 --> 00:25:33,740
- Billy Beane's office.
- Hey.

363
00:25:33,906 --> 00:25:34,949
- Peter Brand.
- Billy.

364
00:25:35,116 --> 00:25:37,618
- How are...? Hi, how you doing?
- Nice to see you.

365
00:25:37,785 --> 00:25:40,371
Good to have you here.
Boy, you move in fast.

366
00:25:40,538 --> 00:25:43,416
Yeah, yeah.
I got here early this morning.

367
00:25:44,917 --> 00:25:47,086
- All moved in.
- Yeah.

368
00:25:47,795 --> 00:25:49,380
Yeah.

369
00:25:49,547 --> 00:25:51,549
Hey, Billy...

370
00:25:51,716 --> 00:25:54,635
I wanted you
to see these player evaluations...

371
00:25:54,802 --> 00:25:56,971
that you asked me to do.

372
00:25:57,930 --> 00:25:59,557
I asked you to do three.

373
00:26:00,475 --> 00:26:01,809
Yeah.

374
00:26:01,976 --> 00:26:04,562
- To evaluate three players.
- Yeah.

375
00:26:04,729 --> 00:26:06,689
How many did you do?

376
00:26:06,856 --> 00:26:08,816
Forty-seven.

377
00:26:09,734 --> 00:26:11,277
Okay.

378
00:26:12,153 --> 00:26:15,907
Actually, 51.
I don't know why I lied just then.

379
00:26:24,916 --> 00:26:27,335
Why don't you walk me
through the board?

380
00:26:28,795 --> 00:26:30,379
Thank you.

381
00:26:56,656 --> 00:26:58,699
Using this equation
in the upper left...

382
00:26:58,866 --> 00:27:01,994
I'm projecting that we need to win
at least 99 games...

383
00:27:02,161 --> 00:27:04,330
in order to make it
to the postseason.

384
00:27:04,497 --> 00:27:08,626
We need to score at least 814 runs
in order to win those games...

385
00:27:08,793 --> 00:27:11,879
and allow no more than 645 runs.

386
00:27:17,009 --> 00:27:18,302
<i>What's this?</i>

387
00:27:18,469 --> 00:27:22,056
<i>This is a code that I've written
for our year-to-year projections.</i>

388
00:27:22,223 --> 00:27:25,893
<i>This is building in the intelligence
that we have to project players.</i>

389
00:27:26,060 --> 00:27:27,061
<i>Okay.</i>

390
00:27:27,228 --> 00:27:29,897
<i>It's about getting things down
to one number.</i>

391
00:27:30,356 --> 00:27:32,900
<i>Using the stats
the way we read them...</i>

392
00:27:33,067 --> 00:27:36,237
<i>we'll find value in players
that nobody else can see.</i>

393
00:27:39,740 --> 00:27:41,075
<i>People are overlooked...</i>

394
00:27:41,242 --> 00:27:45,037
<i>for a variety of biased reasons
and perceived flaws.</i>

395
00:27:45,204 --> 00:27:48,499
<i>Age, appearance, personality.</i>

396
00:27:48,666 --> 00:27:53,421
<i>Bill James and mathematics
cut straight through that.</i>

397
00:27:55,006 --> 00:27:58,301
<i>Billy, of the 20, 000 notable players
for us to consider...</i>

398
00:27:58,467 --> 00:28:01,012
<i>I believe
that there is a championship team...</i>

399
00:28:01,179 --> 00:28:04,348
of 25 people that we can afford...

400
00:28:04,515 --> 00:28:07,685
because everyone else in baseball
undervalues them.

401
00:28:07,852 --> 00:28:11,105
Like an island of misfit toys.

402
00:28:15,568 --> 00:28:18,779
<i>Billy, this is Chad Bradford.</i>
<i>He's a relief pitcher.</i>

403
00:28:18,946 --> 00:28:23,242
<i>He is one of the most undervalued
players in baseball.</i>

404
00:28:23,409 --> 00:28:26,370
<i>His defect is that he throws funny.</i>

405
00:28:27,205 --> 00:28:31,292
<i>Nobody in the big leagues cares
about him because he looks funny.</i>

406
00:28:31,459 --> 00:28:34,545
<i>This guy could be not just
the best pitcher in our pen...</i>

407
00:28:34,712 --> 00:28:38,132
<i>but one of the most effective
relief pitchers in all baseball.</i>

408
00:28:38,299 --> 00:28:41,052
<i>This guy should cost $3 million
a year.</i>

409
00:28:41,219 --> 00:28:44,096
<i>We can get him for 237, 000.</i>

410
00:29:07,995 --> 00:29:09,455
Billy.

411
00:29:10,957 --> 00:29:13,376
- That it?
- Yeah.

412
00:29:43,531 --> 00:29:44,865
Hey, Art.

413
00:29:45,032 --> 00:29:47,243
Can I talk to you
before you get started?

414
00:29:47,410 --> 00:29:49,870
- I'm a bit busy right now.
- I know.

415
00:29:51,747 --> 00:29:53,332
- I know.
- Okay.

416
00:29:53,499 --> 00:29:55,167
- Morning, everyone.
- Art.

417
00:29:55,334 --> 00:29:58,587
- Peter Brand. Nice to meet you.
- Where the hell's Pete?

418
00:29:58,754 --> 00:29:59,839
That's Pete.

419
00:30:00,715 --> 00:30:03,217
Grab a seat. I'll be right back.

420
00:30:04,760 --> 00:30:07,638
- All right, where did you say he's at?
- Okay. He's on...

421
00:30:08,347 --> 00:30:11,017
- Who's the kid?
- A friend of mine.

422
00:30:12,768 --> 00:30:15,730
I can't manage this team
under a one-year contract.

423
00:30:15,896 --> 00:30:17,690
Well, sure you can.

424
00:30:19,400 --> 00:30:21,527
No, I can't.

425
00:30:21,694 --> 00:30:24,238
Okay. I gotta put a team on the field.

426
00:30:24,405 --> 00:30:27,908
After that, I'll take a good long look
at your contract.

427
00:30:28,075 --> 00:30:31,370
Deal with the manager's contract,
then put a team on the field.

428
00:30:31,537 --> 00:30:35,916
At this moment, if a grounder's hit
to first, nobody's there to stop it.

429
00:30:36,751 --> 00:30:41,088
It's not easy doing what I do
under the cloud of a one-year contract.

430
00:30:41,255 --> 00:30:42,673
Okay, I understand that.

431
00:30:42,840 --> 00:30:44,800
- I've been there.
- I know you have.

432
00:30:44,967 --> 00:30:49,430
A one-year contract means the same
thing to a manager as to a player.

433
00:30:49,597 --> 00:30:51,766
There's not a lot of faith there.

434
00:30:51,932 --> 00:30:54,727
Which is strange
after a 102-win season.

435
00:30:55,770 --> 00:30:57,730
I see.

436
00:30:57,897 --> 00:31:02,234
If you lose the last game
of the season, nobody gives a shit.

437
00:31:04,278 --> 00:31:08,115
- So it's on me now?
- No, Art, it's on me.

438
00:31:08,282 --> 00:31:11,619
And the kid is the new assistant GM.

439
00:31:11,786 --> 00:31:13,788
- Okay.
- Okay, fellas.

440
00:31:13,954 --> 00:31:15,623
Hey, Billy.

441
00:31:25,966 --> 00:31:28,719
You can't deny his offensive output.
He can play.

442
00:31:28,886 --> 00:31:31,889
And we need people that can play.

443
00:31:38,104 --> 00:31:40,481
Who do you wanna talk about first?

444
00:31:57,248 --> 00:31:59,250
None of them.

445
00:32:00,000 --> 00:32:02,962
Billy, we got 38 home runs,
120 RBIs to make up for.

446
00:32:03,129 --> 00:32:05,506
Guys, you're still trying
to replace Giambi.

447
00:32:05,673 --> 00:32:09,176
I told you we can't do it,
and we can't do it.

448
00:32:09,718 --> 00:32:13,931
Now, what we might be able to do
is re-create him.

449
00:32:14,098 --> 00:32:17,101
- Re-create him in the aggregate.
- The what?

450
00:32:17,268 --> 00:32:20,020
Giambi's on-base percentage
was .477.

451
00:32:20,187 --> 00:32:24,650
Damon's on-base, .324.
And Olmedo's was .291.

452
00:32:24,817 --> 00:32:27,027
Add that up and you get...

453
00:32:29,697 --> 00:32:30,990
Do you want me to speak?

454
00:32:32,032 --> 00:32:33,868
When I point at you, yeah.

455
00:32:34,034 --> 00:32:36,996
- 1 .092.
- Divided by three.

456
00:32:37,163 --> 00:32:39,915
- .364.
- That's what we're looking for.

457
00:32:40,082 --> 00:32:44,211
Three ballplayers... Three ballplayers
whose average OBP is...

458
00:32:44,378 --> 00:32:45,713
.364.

459
00:32:45,880 --> 00:32:48,757
- Wait, that doesn't come out right.
