00:47:24,466 --> 00:47:26,217
- No?
- No.

694
00:47:26,384 --> 00:47:29,095
Baseball isn't just numbers.
It's not science.

695
00:47:29,262 --> 00:47:32,432
If it was, anybody could do
what we're doing, but they can't.

696
00:47:32,599 --> 00:47:34,351
They don't know what we know.

697
00:47:34,517 --> 00:47:37,604
They don't have our experience
and our intuition.

698
00:47:38,104 --> 00:47:39,230
Okay.

699
00:47:39,814 --> 00:47:43,276
You got a kid in there that's got
a degree in economics from Yale.

700
00:47:43,443 --> 00:47:46,613
You got a scout here
with 29 years of baseball experience.

701
00:47:46,780 --> 00:47:49,366
You're listening to the wrong one.

702
00:47:49,532 --> 00:47:53,370
Now, there are intangibles
that only baseball people understand.

703
00:47:53,536 --> 00:47:56,790
You're discounting
what scouts have done for 150 years?

704
00:47:56,956 --> 00:47:59,000
Even yourself?

705
00:47:59,667 --> 00:48:01,836
Adapt or die.

706
00:48:04,631 --> 00:48:06,966
This is about you and your shit,
isn't it?

707
00:48:07,133 --> 00:48:10,136
Twenty years ago,
some scout got it wrong.

708
00:48:10,303 --> 00:48:12,889
- Okay. Okay.
- Now you declare war on the system.

709
00:48:13,056 --> 00:48:17,769
Okay, okay, my turn.
You don't have a crystal ball.

710
00:48:17,936 --> 00:48:21,523
You can't look at a kid and predict
his future any more than I can.

711
00:48:21,689 --> 00:48:23,983
I've sat at those kitchen tables
with you...

712
00:48:24,150 --> 00:48:27,153
and listened to you tell parents,
"When I know, I know.

713
00:48:27,320 --> 00:48:29,322
And when it comes to your son,
I know."

714
00:48:29,489 --> 00:48:31,950
And you don't.

715
00:48:33,535 --> 00:48:35,328
You don't.

716
00:48:37,831 --> 00:48:40,291
Okay. I don't give a shit
about friendship...

717
00:48:40,458 --> 00:48:43,002
this situation, or the past.

718
00:48:43,169 --> 00:48:46,798
Major League Baseball thinks
the way I think. You're not gonna win.

719
00:48:46,965 --> 00:48:49,551
And I'll give you a nickel's worth
of free advice.

720
00:48:49,717 --> 00:48:52,011
You're never gonna
get another job...

721
00:48:52,178 --> 00:48:55,765
after this catastrophic season
you're about to set us all up for.

722
00:48:55,932 --> 00:48:57,934
You'll have to explain to your kid...

723
00:48:58,101 --> 00:49:00,645
why you're working
at Dick's Sporting Goods.

724
00:49:06,401 --> 00:49:08,862
I'm not gonna fire you, Grady.

725
00:49:12,699 --> 00:49:15,869
- Fuck you, Billy.
- Now I will.

726
00:49:19,706 --> 00:49:21,624
Good luck, Art.

727
00:49:27,714 --> 00:49:30,800
Kubota.
You never played ball, right?

728
00:49:30,967 --> 00:49:33,803
- I played a little T-ball.
- You're the new head scout.

729
00:49:33,970 --> 00:49:35,680
Congratulations.

730
00:49:44,105 --> 00:49:46,441
So Boston's gonna wait and see?

731
00:49:48,067 --> 00:49:49,402
Yeah.

732
00:49:50,737 --> 00:49:53,239
- Yeah.
- It's just you and me, Pete.

733
00:49:53,406 --> 00:49:55,158
And we're all in.

734
00:49:58,995 --> 00:50:01,956
<i>It sounds like you're apologizing
for what they're doing.</i>

735
00:50:02,123 --> 00:50:04,834
<i>I'm not. I just don't know
what you're gonna do...</i>

736
00:50:05,001 --> 00:50:08,379
<i>with the budget that the A's have.</i>
<i>Who are you gonna get?</i>

737
00:50:08,546 --> 00:50:10,715
<i>I'm looking
at the spring-training roster.</i>

738
00:50:10,882 --> 00:50:12,592
<i>- You gotta be kidding me.
- How so?</i>

739
00:50:12,759 --> 00:50:14,886
<i>- He looked like a clown out there.
- Who?</i>

740
00:50:16,262 --> 00:50:18,640
<i>- Chad Bradford.
- Tell me about Bradford.</i>

741
00:50:18,806 --> 00:50:21,267
<i>I like him a little bit,
but he's a specialist.</i>

742
00:50:21,434 --> 00:50:24,479
<i>He's not a guy that you say,</i>
"<i>The eighth inning is yours...</i>

743
00:50:24,646 --> 00:50:26,481
<i>lefties vs. righties.</i>"

744
00:50:26,648 --> 00:50:28,316
<i>In my opinion.</i>

745
00:50:28,483 --> 00:50:30,944
<i>I don't know what Billy Beane
and management...</i>

746
00:50:31,110 --> 00:50:32,445
<i>understands about him.</i>

747
00:50:32,612 --> 00:50:35,281
<i>He only throws the ball
about 82, 83 miles an hour.</i>

748
00:50:35,448 --> 00:50:38,868
<i>- There must be something...
- He is a freak, and not in a good way.</i>

749
00:50:40,245 --> 00:50:43,456
<i>- Let me ask you this.
- Talking about trying to win a division.</i>

750
00:50:43,623 --> 00:50:45,959
<i>We're counting on David
to be the guy he was.</i>

751
00:50:46,125 --> 00:50:48,628
<i>I have my doubts. He's gotten old.</i>

752
00:50:48,795 --> 00:50:52,298
<i>That's why he's not in New York
anymore, not in Cleveland anymore.</i>

753
00:50:52,465 --> 00:50:55,802
<i>We paid him the money we should've
been giving to Johnny Damon.</i>

754
00:50:55,969 --> 00:50:57,053
<i>- Hey.
- Jeremy Giambi.</i>

755
00:50:58,429 --> 00:51:00,014
<i>That's the one to worry about.</i>

756
00:51:00,181 --> 00:51:02,976
<i>He gets comps up and down Vegas
more than in Oakland.</i>

757
00:51:03,142 --> 00:51:05,478
<i>That should tell you something
right there.</i>

758
00:51:05,645 --> 00:51:09,232
<i>- Isn't that the deal with these guys?
- He has one good year.</i>

759
00:51:09,607 --> 00:51:13,069
<i>And he gets a huge offer
and then he gets traded.</i>

760
00:51:15,446 --> 00:51:18,575
- Bob. Harder.
- Hatteberg.

761
00:51:21,661 --> 00:51:24,914
Good. Good.

762
00:51:25,832 --> 00:51:28,001
<i>Billy, we have to talk
about Hatteberg.</i>

763
00:51:28,167 --> 00:51:30,628
- Go.
- There's just no feel for the spot.

764
00:51:30,795 --> 00:51:34,340
I think it's a long shot that he can be
a big-league first baseman.

765
00:51:34,507 --> 00:51:37,802
It's day one of the first week.
You can't judge this yet.

766
00:51:37,969 --> 00:51:39,554
No, I think we can judge it.

767
00:51:39,721 --> 00:51:44,017
I mean, I like him, you know,
but I can judge him.

768
00:51:44,183 --> 00:51:45,810
First base is the moon to him.

769
00:51:45,977 --> 00:51:49,856
It wasn't to Giambi. Giambi's the worst
first baseman in baseball.

770
00:51:50,023 --> 00:51:53,526
- Gonna compare him to Giambi?
- What are we talking about?

771
00:51:53,693 --> 00:51:54,986
All right.

772
00:51:56,988 --> 00:51:58,281
What do you think, Wash?

773
00:51:58,823 --> 00:52:02,285
The nice way to say it
is he lacks confidence.

774
00:52:02,452 --> 00:52:03,953
Well, give him some.

775
00:52:04,662 --> 00:52:07,248
I'll do that, but we got Peña,
who can play first.

776
00:52:07,415 --> 00:52:09,834
And he's looking mighty good
out there.

777
00:52:10,627 --> 00:52:12,712
We wanna go with Hattie.

778
00:52:17,717 --> 00:52:19,302
We got six weeks.

779
00:52:19,469 --> 00:52:21,387
Get down in it.

780
00:52:27,518 --> 00:52:28,853
- There you go.
- Scotty H.

781
00:52:29,020 --> 00:52:31,689
- That's what I'm talking about.
- Picking machine.

782
00:52:31,856 --> 00:52:34,192
It's only baseball.

783
00:52:40,365 --> 00:52:42,408
This better work.

784
00:52:43,743 --> 00:52:45,662
I'm just kidding you.

785
00:52:59,092 --> 00:53:01,969
<i>Let's go, Oakland!</i>

786
00:53:02,136 --> 00:53:04,430
<i>Let's go, Oakland!</i>

787
00:53:06,891 --> 00:53:10,269
- What is wrong with this thing?
- It's a dollar, man.

788
00:53:10,436 --> 00:53:12,855
- What?
- Welcome to Oakland, D.J.

789
00:53:13,022 --> 00:53:15,066
Oh, you gotta be shitting me.

790
00:53:15,233 --> 00:53:19,070
I think this year, we're gonna show
that it takes a team to win...

791
00:53:19,237 --> 00:53:21,406
not any individual guy,
just a team.

792
00:53:21,572 --> 00:53:24,951
And I think we got
a hell of a ball club here.

793
00:53:25,118 --> 00:53:27,161
Chad, are you intimidated
at all today?

794
00:53:27,328 --> 00:53:32,542
I wouldn't say I'm intimidated, really.
I'm just really excited, like you said.

795
00:53:32,709 --> 00:53:36,212
Jeremy, how's the team gonna fare
without your brother, Jason?

796
00:53:36,379 --> 00:53:39,090
Well, you know,
the organization did a great job...

797
00:53:39,257 --> 00:53:41,968
of bringing in good young guys
to fill that role.

798
00:53:42,135 --> 00:53:44,554
Let's face it,
they're getting a deal with you.

799
00:53:44,721 --> 00:53:46,973
The Yankees are paying Jason a lot
of money.

800
00:53:47,140 --> 00:53:50,226
You are coming here on a dime.
How does that make you feel?

801
00:53:50,393 --> 00:53:52,311
I feel good.

802
00:53:52,478 --> 00:53:55,481
- How are the nerves in your fingers?
- You know.

803
00:53:55,648 --> 00:53:57,692
Gotta start with the age,
36 years old.

804
00:53:57,859 --> 00:54:00,111
How do you think
your body's gonna hold up?

805
00:54:00,278 --> 00:54:03,489
You spend a lot of time at strip clubs,
partying.

806
00:54:03,656 --> 00:54:06,242
Do you resent the attention you get
off the field?

807
00:54:06,409 --> 00:54:07,452
I love it.

808
00:54:07,618 --> 00:54:09,829
- You spend a lot of time in Vegas.
- I do.

809
00:54:09,996 --> 00:54:14,208
- I feel great. I did a lot of work to get...
- Excuse me. Get out of my shot.

810
00:54:14,375 --> 00:54:15,418
Sorry, go ahead.

811
00:54:15,585 --> 00:54:17,712
There have been questions
about my age...

812
00:54:17,879 --> 00:54:21,632
and my declining skills, some say,
but I'm here to prove that wrong.

813
00:54:21,799 --> 00:54:23,509
I asked if you were 100 percent.

814
00:54:32,477 --> 00:54:34,353
- Excuse me, Mr. Beane?
- Hey, Chad.

815
00:54:34,520 --> 00:54:37,815
- Hey, I'm not disturbing you, am I?
- Not at all. What's up?

816
00:54:37,982 --> 00:54:41,068
I wanted to say thank you
for this opportunity.

817
00:54:41,235 --> 00:54:44,697
Well, we enjoy having you.
It's gonna work out well for all of us.

818
00:54:44,864 --> 00:54:48,785
I appreciate it, sir. Nobody's ever
given me a chance like this before.

819
00:54:49,368 --> 00:54:50,453
Nobody?

820
00:54:51,537 --> 00:54:53,623
Well, just you, sir.

821
00:54:54,207 --> 00:54:57,543
Well, it's a big day,
one you won't forget.

822
00:54:57,710 --> 00:54:59,879
Appreciate it.
And I wanna let you know...

823
00:55:00,046 --> 00:55:02,882
I'm gonna be praying for you
and your family.

824
00:55:03,424 --> 00:55:05,218
No problem.

825
00:55:05,843 --> 00:55:09,430
Well, here we are just minutes away
from the season opener of 2002...

826
00:55:09,597 --> 00:55:10,807
for the Oakland A's.

827
00:55:10,973 --> 00:55:12,683
The first pitch is moments away.

828
00:55:12,850 --> 00:55:14,977
We'll come back
with the national anthem.

829
00:55:15,144 --> 00:55:16,562
Opening day is upon us.

830
00:55:17,063 --> 00:55:20,566
All right, fellas, smile. Here we go.

831
00:55:28,908 --> 00:55:30,910
I'm going in.
Text me the play-by-play.

832
00:55:31,077 --> 00:55:32,662
What? Why?

833
00:55:33,579 --> 00:55:35,540
I don't watch the games.

834
00:55:44,090 --> 00:55:45,675
Detail, halt!

835
00:55:47,051 --> 00:55:49,929
And forward face!

836
00:56:50,489 --> 00:56:53,159
<i>That's the third Ranger batter
to be hit today.</i>

837
00:56:53,326 --> 00:56:57,830
<i>Twice Alex Rodriguez was nicked.
The ninth...</i>

838
00:57:31,989 --> 00:57:35,701
I should've made you a bigger part
of the conversation from day one.

839
00:57:35,868 --> 00:57:37,870
It'd be clear what we're trying to do.

840
00:57:38,037 --> 00:57:40,998
That was my mistake, Art.
I take responsibility for that.

841
00:57:41,165 --> 00:57:44,543
- What are you trying to say?
- Doesn't matter what moves I make...

842
00:57:44,710 --> 00:57:47,713
if you don't play the team
the way they're designed to be.

843
00:57:49,548 --> 00:57:51,842
Billy, you're out of your depth.

844
00:57:53,010 --> 00:57:56,055
- Why not Hatteberg at first?
- Because he can't play first.

845
00:57:56,222 --> 00:57:58,641
- How do you know?
- Not my first baseball game.

846
00:57:58,808 --> 00:58:01,519
- Scott Hatteberg can't hit.
- He gets on base.

847
00:58:01,686 --> 00:58:05,064
Still keeps us in the plus column.
We need to be seven over .500.

848
00:58:05,231 --> 00:58:06,816
What?

849
00:58:10,236 --> 00:58:12,363
Anything else?

850
00:58:12,530 --> 00:58:16,784
Yeah. I would've rather seen
Bradford in the end than Magnante.

851
00:58:17,410 --> 00:58:18,452
Bradford's a righty.

852
00:58:18,619 --> 00:58:21,747
- I don't care about righty-lefty.
- I do.

853
00:58:26,377 --> 00:58:29,505
- Could this be about your contract?
- No.

854
00:58:30,256 --> 00:58:34,051
This is about you doing your job
and me doing mine.

855
00:58:34,218 --> 00:58:35,761
Mine's me being left alone...

856
00:58:35,928 --> 00:58:38,848
to manage this team
you assembled for me.

857
00:58:39,015 --> 00:58:42,601
- I didn't assemble them for you, Art.
- No shit.

858
00:58:50,985 --> 00:58:52,445
Good meeting.

859
00:58:52,611 --> 00:58:53,738
Every time we talk...

860
00:58:53,904 --> 00:58:56,699
I'm reinvigorated
by my love of the game.

861
00:59:20,056 --> 00:59:23,476
<i>We got Grady Fuson, former head
of scouting with the Athletics.</i>

862
00:59:23,642 --> 00:59:26,437
<i>And, Grady, can you interpret for us
what's going on?</i>

863
00:59:26,604 --> 00:59:28,773
<i>- They call it Moneyball.
- Moneyball?</i>

864
00:59:28,939 --> 00:59:33,486
<i>Yes, and it was a nice theory,
and now it's just not working out.</i>

865
00:59:33,652 --> 00:59:37,656
<i>Billy Beane has built this team
on the ideas of a guy, Bill James...</i>

866
00:59:37,823 --> 00:59:42,495
<i>who wrote an interesting book
on baseball statistics.</i>

867
00:59:42,661 --> 00:59:46,665
<i>The problem is that Bill James
never played, never managed.</i>

868
00:59:46,832 --> 00:59:50,169
<i>He was in fact a security guard
at a pork-and-beans company.</i>

869
00:59:51,545 --> 00:59:54,256
<i>Do you see this as a decimation
of the organization?</i>

870
00:59:54,423 --> 00:59:56,926
- <i>He bought a ticket on the</i> Titanic.
<i>- Oh, boy.</i>

871
00:59:57,093 --> 00:59:59,345
<i>He's tried to come up
with a new approach.</i>

872
00:59:59,512 --> 01:00:02,765
<i>My hat's</i> off <i>to him. It won't work.</i>

873
01:00:03,516 --> 01:00:06,560
<i>One-two pitch. Tejada strikes out.</i>

874
01:00:06,727 --> 01:00:07,895
<i>And that is the game.</i>

875
01:00:08,062 --> 01:00:11,148
<i>The Seattle Mariners
win both games on this series, Ray.</i>

876
01:00:11,315 --> 01:00:14,860
<i>They've won 10 in a row.
Seattle is 13 and 3.</i>

877
01:00:17,530 --> 01:00:19,865
I can't watch this shit.

878
01:00:20,991 --> 01:00:22,535
Go on the road with the team.

879
01:00:22,701 --> 01:00:24,912
You don't go on the road
with the team.

880
01:00:25,079 --> 01:00:28,707
- That's why I want you to do it.
- Why don't you?

881
01:00:30,209 --> 01:00:33,045
I can't develop personal relationships
with these guys.

882
01:00:33,212 --> 01:00:37,758
I gotta be able to trade them,
send them down, sometimes cut them.

883
01:00:39,927 --> 01:00:42,888
Which is something
you should learn to do, by the way.

884
01:00:45,558 --> 01:00:48,644
I would never have to cut a player,
unless you...

885
01:00:49,395 --> 01:00:52,398
- Oh, come on.
- "Come on" what?

886
01:00:52,565 --> 01:00:55,067
- Let's practice.
- No.

887
01:00:55,234 --> 01:00:58,112
Yeah. I'm a player.
You gotta cut me from the roster.

888
01:00:58,279 --> 01:00:59,321
- No.
- Go.

889
01:00:59,488 --> 01:01:00,948
- What do you mean, no?
- No.

890
01:01:01,115 --> 01:01:02,741
- Do it.
- This is stupid.

891
01:01:03,200 --> 01:01:05,327
Part of the job, man.

892
01:01:09,748 --> 01:01:11,250
Fine.

893
01:01:12,585 --> 01:01:16,046
Billy, please have a seat.
I need to talk to you for a minute.

894
01:01:16,213 --> 01:01:17,756
Go on.

895
01:01:19,091 --> 01:01:21,177
You've been a huge part
of this team.

896
01:01:21,343 --> 01:01:24,138
But sometimes you have to
make decisions for the team.

897
01:01:24,305 --> 01:01:25,931
I'm sure you can understand.

898
01:01:26,098 --> 01:01:29,101
- You're cutting me?
- I'm really sorry.

899
01:01:29,935 --> 01:01:31,437
I just bought a house here.

900
01:01:31,604 --> 01:01:33,272
- Well...
- In Oakland.

901
01:01:37,026 --> 01:01:38,611
Well... Well...

902
01:01:38,777 --> 01:01:42,031
"Well... Well..."?
That's all you got to say?

903
01:01:42,198 --> 01:01:44,575
My kid just started a new school.

904
01:01:44,742 --> 01:01:48,078
- They made friends.
- That's...

905
01:01:48,621 --> 01:01:51,457
You shouldn't pull them out
in the middle of the year.

906
01:01:51,624 --> 01:01:54,460
- You should wait.
- What the hell are you talking about?

907
01:01:54,627 --> 01:01:56,462
I don't know. I shouldn't have...

908
01:01:56,629 --> 01:01:59,131
I'm not gonna do this.
I think this is stupid.

909
01:01:59,298 --> 01:02:02,468
I'm not gonna fire anybody,
and this is dumb.

910
01:02:03,552 --> 01:02:06,805
They're professional ballplayers.
Just be straight with them.

911
01:02:06,972 --> 01:02:08,933
No fluff, just facts.

912
01:02:09,099 --> 01:02:13,938
Pete, I gotta let you go.
Jack's office will handle the details.

913
01:02:16,649 --> 01:02:18,192
That's it?

914
01:02:19,276 --> 01:02:20,319
Really?

915
01:02:20,486 --> 01:02:24,907
You rather get a bullet to the head or
five to the chest and bleed to death?

916
01:02:26,492 --> 01:02:29,161
Are those my only two options?

917
01:02:29,328 --> 01:02:31,497
Go on the road with the team.

918
01:02:34,124 --> 01:02:35,751
Okay.

919
01:02:45,094 --> 01:02:46,637
Say, bro.

920
01:02:46,804 --> 01:02:48,847
- Let me ask you a question.
- Yeah.

921
01:02:49,014 --> 01:02:51,850
How come your boss doesn't travel
with the team?

922
01:02:53,727 --> 01:02:57,314
He doesn't like to mingle
with the players.

923
01:02:59,108 --> 01:03:01,694
Is that supposed to make us
easier to cut?

924
01:03:06,907 --> 01:03:09,034
I don't know. I don't know.

925
01:03:09,201 --> 01:03:14,039
And how come soda
is a dollar in the clubhouse?

926
01:03:14,206 --> 01:03:16,458
I never seen nothing like that.

927
01:03:17,710 --> 01:03:20,546
Billy likes to keep the money
on the field.

928
01:03:20,713 --> 01:03:22,589
Soda money?

929
01:03:23,048 --> 01:03:24,591
Really?

930
01:03:25,092 --> 01:03:28,512
Where on the field
is the dollar I'm paying for soda?

931
01:03:30,097 --> 01:03:33,559
It's hard to see exactly...

932
01:03:33,726 --> 01:03:36,687
- but it's there, yeah.
- Yeah, it is hard to see.

933
01:03:37,313 --> 01:03:38,897
I'm done.

934
01:03:50,034 --> 01:03:52,786
- Hey, Dad.
- Hi, honey.

935
01:03:52,953 --> 01:03:54,955
- How are you?
- I'm good.

936
01:03:55,122 --> 01:03:57,249
- Was it bumpy?
- It was okay.

937
01:03:59,710 --> 01:04:02,379
<i>So with this loss tonight,
the Oakland Athletics...</i>

938
01:04:02,546 --> 01:04:05,716
<i>incredibly, have lost 14
of their last 17 games.</i>

939
01:04:07,801 --> 01:04:10,888
<i>They are 10 games back
in the American League West.</i>

940
01:04:11,055 --> 01:04:13,557
<i>Is it fair to say
the experiment has failed?</i>

941
01:04:13,724 --> 01:04:16,060
<i>Well, absolutely. It was predictable.</i>

942
01:04:16,226 --> 01:04:19,188
<i>You don't wish anybody
a lack of success...</i>

943
01:04:19,355 --> 01:04:22,775
<i>- but the facts are in front of you.
- You can't blame Art Howe.</i>

944
01:04:22,941 --> 01:04:24,985
<i>- No.
- The fact of the matter is...</i>

945
01:04:25,152 --> 01:04:28,197
<i>this is not about statistics,
this is about people.</i>

946
01:04:28,364 --> 01:04:31,116
<i>Art Howe is not the problem.</i>

947
01:04:31,283 --> 01:04:33,952
<i>The problem
is in the general manager's office...</i>

948
01:04:34,119 --> 01:04:35,204
<i>with Billy Beane.</i>

949
01:04:35,371 --> 01:04:37,956
<i>The root of the problem for me
is philosophical.</i>

950
01:04:38,123 --> 01:04:40,376
<i>I said it before.
This is fantasy baseball.</i>

951
01:04:40,876 --> 01:04:42,336
<i>Billy is just not thinking.</i>

952
01:04:42,503 --> 01:04:45,130
<i>Start thinking about a new GM,
making changes.</i>

953
01:04:45,297 --> 01:04:46,715
<i>He never goes to the games.</i>

954
01:04:46,882 --> 01:04:51,303
<i>- This was very predictable.
- He needs to look at what's going on.</i>

955
01:04:51,470 --> 01:04:54,932
<i>- The man needs to get real.
- I want Billy Beane gone.</i>

956
01:04:55,099 --> 01:04:57,559
<i>Calling for Beane's head.
I want your thoughts.</i>

957
01:04:57,726 --> 01:05:02,940
<i>The past 18 games, they've been
shut out or scored one run four times.</i>

958
01:05:03,107 --> 01:05:04,817
<i>They're just not scoring enough.</i>

959
01:05:04,983 --> 01:05:08,153
<i>It's not just the offense,
not Thad Bosley and the hitters.</i>

960
01:05:08,320 --> 01:05:12,616
<i>It's everything. if there was one thing
you could pick out, you'd try to fix it...</i>

961
01:05:12,783 --> 01:05:18,122
<i>but just everything is in a funk
right now.</i>

962
01:05:22,709 --> 01:05:25,295
What the hell am I doing?

963
01:05:27,673 --> 01:05:30,426
Oh, man.

964
01:05:30,592 --> 01:05:32,594
Look, Steve.

965
01:05:36,140 --> 01:05:38,267
I believe in what we're doing.

966
01:05:38,434 --> 01:05:41,311
The record doesn't reflect the strength
of this team...

967
01:05:41,478 --> 01:05:44,189
or where we're gonna be
at the end of the season.

968
01:05:44,356 --> 01:05:48,986
Now, Pete and I here feel very strongly
that we stay on the track we've chosen.

969
01:05:49,153 --> 01:05:51,697
Our sample size has been too small.
It's too...

970
01:05:51,864 --> 01:05:53,532
Early. It's still early.

971
01:05:54,199 --> 01:05:57,286
Where do we expect to be
by the All-Star break?

972
01:05:58,454 --> 01:06:00,956
Our goal and our expectation...

973
01:06:01,123 --> 01:06:04,877
is by mid-July
to be within seven games of first.

974
01:06:05,043 --> 01:06:06,503
That would be this working.

975
01:06:06,670 --> 01:06:09,173
- That keeps us in the hunt.
- Exceptionally well.

976
01:06:09,715 --> 01:06:12,593
- By July.
- July.

977
01:06:12,759 --> 01:06:16,638
And what's gonna prevent you
from accomplishing that?

978
01:06:16,805 --> 01:06:18,474
What are you afraid of?

979
01:06:18,640 --> 01:06:21,560
Nothing.
That's why we're here, Steve.

980
01:06:21,727 --> 01:06:25,063
That's why we get up in the morning.
That's all we do.

981
01:06:44,625 --> 01:06:46,168
- More?
- Yeah, a little more.

982
01:06:46,335 --> 01:06:49,796
- Don't tell your mother.
- I won't.

983
01:06:50,547 --> 01:06:52,674
- Chocolate sauce?
- Yes.

984
01:06:53,509 --> 01:06:54,927
Stop.

985
01:06:57,513 --> 01:07:00,474
- Big spoon or little spoon?
- Little spoon.

986
01:07:01,850 --> 01:07:03,519
Thank you.

987
01:07:13,195 --> 01:07:16,323
Dad, there's no way
you're gonna lose your job, right?

988
01:07:16,490 --> 01:07:17,950
What?

989
01:07:18,784 --> 01:07:22,162
- Well, I don't know. I'm just wondering.
- Where'd you hear that?

990
01:07:22,329 --> 01:07:24,289
Well, I go on the Internet sometimes.

991
01:07:24,456 --> 01:07:27,626
Well, don't do that.
Don't go on the Internet.

992
01:07:27,793 --> 01:07:30,629
Or watch TV or read newspapers...

993
01:07:31,421 --> 01:07:33,340
or talk to people.

994
01:07:33,507 --> 01:07:36,176
I don't talk to people.
I just read stuff.

995
01:07:36,343 --> 01:07:38,971
Honey, everything's fine.
Everything's fine.

996
01:07:39,721 --> 01:07:41,598
Really, you don't have to worry.

997
01:07:41,765 --> 01:07:45,143
But if you lose your job,
will you have to move away?

998
01:07:45,894 --> 01:07:48,313
Honey, I'm not gonna lose my job.

999
01:07:49,731 --> 01:07:51,733
You don't have to worry.

1000
01:07:54,111 --> 01:07:56,488
- Okay.
- Hey.

1001
01:07:57,072 --> 01:08:00,450
- There's no problem.
- Okay.

1002
01:08:00,617 --> 01:08:03,954
All right? I got uptown problems,
which are not problems at all.

1003
01:08:04,955 --> 01:08:06,331
You're not worried, right?

1004
01:08:06,498 --> 01:08:09,001
- No, I'm not worried.
- Okay.

1005
01:08:16,300 --> 01:08:17,968
Peña.

1006
01:08:20,637 --> 01:08:22,264
Okay.

1007
01:08:35,068 --> 01:08:37,195
I want Dye in right...

1008
01:08:37,362 --> 01:08:40,198
Justice DH-ing,
Peña on the bench...

1009
01:08:40,365 --> 01:08:42,159
Hatteberg at first...

1010
01:08:42,326 --> 01:08:45,370
and anyone but Mags
first out of the pen.

1011
01:08:45,537 --> 01:08:47,456
You want Peña on the bench?

1012
01:08:47,623 --> 01:08:50,751
That's right. So you can play Hattie.

1013
01:08:50,917 --> 01:08:53,170
Peña is not only
the best first baseman...

1014
01:08:53,337 --> 01:08:55,505
he's the only first baseman.

1015
01:08:55,672 --> 01:08:58,050
Hattie gets on base more than Peña.

1016
01:08:58,216 --> 01:09:00,719
- In fact, 20 percent more.
- And his fielding?

1017
01:09:00,886 --> 01:09:03,555
His fielding does not matter.

1018
01:09:04,556 --> 01:09:06,808
- I've heard enough of this.
- Have you?

1019
01:09:06,975 --> 01:09:08,560
And I...

1020
01:09:09,394 --> 01:09:12,397
I disagree with you,
plain and simple.

1021
01:09:13,315 --> 01:09:15,484
And moreover,
I'm playing my team...

1022
01:09:15,984 --> 01:09:19,655
in a way that I can explain
in job interviews next winter.

1023
01:09:20,572 --> 01:09:22,240
Okay?

1024
01:09:27,245 --> 01:09:30,248
Hattie. Not Peña.

1025
01:09:34,586 --> 01:09:35,962
What's up, skip?

1026
01:09:36,129 --> 01:09:38,590
- How you doing?
- Good, how you doing, man?

1027
01:09:38,757 --> 01:09:40,384
Get some sleep last night?

1028
01:09:42,511 --> 01:09:45,597
<i>As the A's hit the field,</i>
<i>we are ready for baseball.</i>

1029
01:09:45,764 --> 01:09:49,101
<i>First one out of the dugout
is rookie sensation Carlos Peña...</i>

1030
01:09:49,267 --> 01:09:54,231
<i>one of the few bright lights in this
lineup, taking his spot at first base.</i>

1031
01:10:33,979 --> 01:10:37,566
Billy, quick question. Do you expect
these guys to produce more or...?

1032
01:10:37,733 --> 01:10:40,026
- Not now.
- What's the reason for the slump?

1033
01:10:58,336 --> 01:10:59,880
Get down.

1034
01:11:04,050 --> 01:11:06,011
Is losing fun?

1035
01:11:09,222 --> 01:11:12,350
- Is losing fun?
- No.

1036
01:11:16,480 --> 01:11:18,690
What are you having fun for?

1037
01:11:44,090 --> 01:11:46,510
That's what losing sounds like.

1038
01:12:01,066 --> 01:12:02,484
Are you okay, Dad?

1039
01:12:03,235 --> 01:12:05,195
- You're doing it again.
- What?

1040
01:12:05,362 --> 01:12:07,656
You're worrying about me.

1041
01:12:07,864 --> 01:12:09,699
You're in last place, Dad.

1042
01:12:09,866 --> 01:12:12,244
- Do I look worried?
- Yeah.

1043
01:12:12,410 --> 01:12:16,373
Because you're getting on an airplane,
and those things crash all the time.

1044
01:12:16,540 --> 01:12:18,959
Please stop worrying
about your dad.

1045
01:12:21,253 --> 01:12:22,879
- We're all set.
- Okay.

1046
01:12:24,756 --> 01:12:26,925
- I love you.
- Love you too.

1047
01:12:27,384 --> 01:12:30,262
All right. Your dad's not in trouble.

1048
01:12:31,304 --> 01:12:33,265
Okay.

1049
01:13:12,178 --> 01:13:13,972
Yeah.

1050
01:13:19,978 --> 01:13:22,147
- Suzanne, get me Ed Wade.
- Okay.

1051
01:13:22,314 --> 01:13:24,024
- Coffee on?
- Yes.

1052
01:13:24,190 --> 01:13:26,818
- Good morning.
- Good morning, Billy.

1053
01:13:30,405 --> 01:13:32,240
Oh, hi, Louisa.

1054
01:13:32,407 --> 01:13:35,327
- I need Ed Wade for Billy Beane.
- Hi.

1055
01:13:36,494 --> 01:13:37,537
Please hold.

1056
01:13:37,704 --> 01:13:40,332
- What's up?
- Wade's on 2.

1057
01:13:40,498 --> 01:13:41,958
- Ed?
<i>- Hello?</i>

1058
01:13:42,125 --> 01:13:44,544
- Ed, it's Billy.
<i>- Billy, what's up?</i>

1059
01:13:44,711 --> 01:13:47,714
- Look, I need a little help on defense.
<i>- Okay.</i>

1060
01:13:47,881 --> 01:13:50,467
I'm willing to trade Jeremy Giambi
for it.

1061
01:13:51,176 --> 01:13:52,636
<i>- Really?</i>
- What?

1062
01:13:53,511 --> 01:13:54,930
- Who you got?
- What?

1063
01:13:55,096 --> 01:13:58,266
- <i>Well, let me think.</i>
- What are you doing?

1064
01:13:58,433 --> 01:13:59,684
Cleaning house.

1065
01:13:59,851 --> 01:14:01,811
<i>- Mabry?</i>
- Maybe what?

1066
01:14:01,978 --> 01:14:05,023
- <i>No, Mabry.</i>
- Hold on.

1067
01:14:05,190 --> 01:14:07,025
- No.
- Why not?

1068
01:14:07,192 --> 01:14:09,361
Because you can't trade
Jeremy Giambi.

1069
01:14:10,612 --> 01:14:12,113
He'll be fine, Ed.

1070
01:14:12,280 --> 01:14:14,866
<i>Why do I get the feeling
you're picking my pocket?</i>

1071
01:14:15,033 --> 01:14:18,370
I'm not. You're picking mine.
Giambi's name alone is worth more.

1072
01:14:18,536 --> 01:14:20,747
<i>- What's wrong with him?</i>
- Nothing.

1073
01:14:20,914 --> 01:14:24,417
Can we say it's done in theory
and start drawing up the paperwork?

1074
01:14:24,584 --> 01:14:26,836
- <i>Okay, but you're gonna have-</i>-
- Great.

1075
01:14:27,003 --> 01:14:28,713
He was gonna say something else.

1076
01:14:28,880 --> 01:14:31,466
When you get the answer
you're looking for, hang up.

1077
01:14:31,633 --> 01:14:32,676
- Suzanne.
- Yes?

1078
01:14:32,842 --> 01:14:35,303
- David Dombrowski.
- Okay.

1079
01:14:35,470 --> 01:14:38,431
- And Peña's going too.
- I don't think you should do that.

1080
01:14:38,598 --> 01:14:43,061
- I really don't think you should do that.
- I want Hatteberg in the lineup tonight.

1081
01:14:43,228 --> 01:14:44,604
You need to take a minute.

1082
01:14:44,771 --> 01:14:47,899
I think you seriously need to think
about what you're doing.

1083
01:14:48,066 --> 01:14:50,568
- Because you're upset.
- Okay.

1084
01:14:51,069 --> 01:14:52,904
What am I missing?

1085
01:14:53,571 --> 01:14:55,907
These are hard moves
to explain to people.

1086
01:14:56,783 --> 01:14:58,410
Why is that a problem, Pete?

1087
01:15:01,204 --> 01:15:03,415
Don't make
an emotional decision, Billy.

1088
01:15:03,581 --> 01:15:07,961
- David Dombrowski's on 3.
- Look, we're gonna shake things up.

1089
01:15:08,128 --> 01:15:11,172
Dave. Peña's going on the block.
You're my first call.

1090
01:15:12,173 --> 01:15:14,968
Because he's making the rest
of the team look bad.

1091
01:15:15,927 --> 01:15:17,762
He's gonna be a Rookie of the Year.

1092
01:15:17,929 --> 01:15:21,099
- Probably an All-Star.
- He's an All-Star, Dave.

1093
01:15:21,975 --> 01:15:24,769
No. I want a reliever and cash.

1094
01:15:25,270 --> 01:15:28,940
Okay. You got five minutes, Dave.
I'm not waiting.

1095
01:15:29,649 --> 01:15:33,445
Billy, Peña is an All-Star, okay?

1096
01:15:33,611 --> 01:15:37,657
And if you dump him and this
Hatteberg thing doesn't work out...

1097
01:15:37,824 --> 01:15:39,534
you know this is...

1098
01:15:39,701 --> 01:15:42,787
This is the kind of decision
that gets you fired.

1099
01:15:42,954 --> 01:15:44,539
It is.

1100
01:15:45,081 --> 01:15:47,125
Yes, you're right.

1101
01:15:47,584 --> 01:15:49,878
I may lose my job.

1102
01:15:50,045 --> 01:15:53,465
In which case I'm a 44-year-old guy
with a high school diploma...

1103
01:15:53,631 --> 01:15:56,926
and a daughter
I'd like to be able to send to college.

1104
01:15:57,427 --> 01:16:00,472
You're 25 years old,
with a degree from Yale...

1105
01:16:00,638 --> 01:16:03,224
and a pretty impressive
apprenticeship.

1106
01:16:04,059 --> 01:16:06,811
I don't think
we're asking the right question.

1107
01:16:07,312 --> 01:16:10,315
I think the question
we should be asking is...

1108
01:16:10,482 --> 01:16:13,151
do you believe in this thing or not?

1109
01:16:14,986 --> 01:16:16,571
I do.

1110
01:16:19,616 --> 01:16:22,660
It's a problem you think
we need to explain ourselves.

1111
01:16:22,827 --> 01:16:26,039
Don't. To anyone.

1112
01:16:29,417 --> 01:16:30,877
Okay.

1113
01:16:33,421 --> 01:16:36,883
Now, I'm gonna see this thing through,
for better or worse.

1114
01:16:40,345 --> 01:16:45,183
Just tell me, do you project we'll win
more with Hatteberg or Peña at first?

1115
01:16:45,767 --> 01:16:48,186
It's close...

1116
01:16:49,020 --> 01:16:51,439
but theoretically, Hatteberg.

1117
01:16:52,315 --> 01:16:57,320
- What are we talking about, then?
- Dombrowski's on again, on 3.

1118
01:16:59,656 --> 01:17:01,074
Yeah?

1119
01:17:01,783 --> 01:17:03,701
Okay, that'll work.

1120
01:17:04,369 --> 01:17:06,621
Great. I need one more thing.

1121
01:17:06,788 --> 01:17:10,041
Soda. Yeah, I don't want my guys
paying for soda.

1122
01:17:10,208 --> 01:17:12,877
I want you to stock my machine
for three years.

1123
01:17:13,044 --> 01:17:14,546
I'm serious.

1124
01:17:15,547 --> 01:17:17,549
Great. It's a deal.

1125
01:17:18,675 --> 01:17:20,635
Go tell Peña he's gotta pack.

1126
01:17:22,137 --> 01:17:25,348
- You want me to tell Peña?
- Part of the job.

1127
01:17:27,851 --> 01:17:30,270
What about Giambi?
You want me to tell him too?

1128
01:17:30,436 --> 01:17:32,397
I'll tell him.

1129
01:17:39,362 --> 01:17:40,947
- Excuse me, Carlos?
- Yeah?

1130
01:17:41,114 --> 01:17:43,074
- Can I speak with you a minute?
- Yeah.

1131
01:17:51,833 --> 01:17:54,419
Carlos, you've been traded
to the Tigers.

1132
01:17:57,922 --> 01:17:59,924
This is Jay Palmer's number.

1133
01:18:00,091 --> 01:18:02,635
He's the traveling secretary
for the team.

1134
01:18:02,802 --> 01:18:05,847
He's expecting your call.
He'll take care of everything.

1135
01:18:15,106 --> 01:18:17,609
- Is that it?
- Yes.

1136
01:18:24,908 --> 01:18:26,326
Okay.

1137
01:18:38,671 --> 01:18:40,131
Okay.

1138
01:18:42,717 --> 01:18:43,927
Art, you got a minute?

1139
01:18:47,180 --> 01:18:50,225
Yeah. Take a seat.

1140
01:18:53,645 --> 01:18:57,982
You can't start Peña at first tonight.
You'll have to start Hatteberg.

1141
01:18:58,816 --> 01:19:03,821
I don't wanna go 15 rounds, Billy.
The lineup card is mine, and that's all.

1142
01:19:03,988 --> 01:19:05,990
That lineup card is definitely yours.

1143
01:19:06,157 --> 01:19:08,743
I'm just saying you can't start Peña
at first.

1144
01:19:11,829 --> 01:19:13,998
Well, I am starting him at first.

1145
01:19:14,165 --> 01:19:18,127
I don't think so.
He plays for Detroit now.

1146
01:19:22,048 --> 01:19:24,217
You traded Peña?

1147
01:19:25,385 --> 01:19:26,928
Yeah.

1148
01:19:27,095 --> 01:19:31,516
And Menechino, Hiljus, Tam
are all being sent down.

1149
01:19:31,683 --> 01:19:35,979
- You are outside your mind.
- Yeah. Cuckoo.

1150
01:19:37,772 --> 01:19:40,566
- You wanted to see me?
- Yeah, Jeremy, grab a seat.

1151
01:19:44,153 --> 01:19:46,656
Jeremy, you've been traded
to the Phillies.

1152
01:19:46,823 --> 01:19:49,450
This is Ed Wade's number.
He's a good guy, the GM.

1153
01:19:49,617 --> 01:19:51,953
He's expecting your call.

1154
01:19:52,120 --> 01:19:54,956
Buddy will help you
with the plane flight.

1155
01:19:56,291 --> 01:19:59,002
You're a good ballplayer, Jeremy...

1156
01:19:59,168 --> 01:20:01,713
and we wish you the best.

1157
01:20:18,229 --> 01:20:20,315
Jeremy's gone too.

1158
01:20:22,275 --> 01:20:24,402
You're killing this team.

1159
01:20:24,569 --> 01:20:28,239
Art, I can do this all day long.

1160
01:20:34,370 --> 01:20:35,747
Hey.

1161
01:20:36,706 --> 01:20:38,750
You agree with this?

1162
01:20:40,126 --> 01:20:41,836
Hundred percent.

1163
01:20:43,379 --> 01:20:44,922
You want this door closed?

1164
01:20:57,477 --> 01:20:59,937
- Scotty H.
- Sir?

1165
01:21:00,938 --> 01:21:04,609
- Go field some grounders.
- Yes, sir.

1166
01:21:04,776 --> 01:21:06,611
Everybody, listen up.

1167
01:21:09,614 --> 01:21:12,367
You may not look
like a winning team...

1168
01:21:15,620 --> 01:21:17,705
but you are one.

1169
01:21:25,004 --> 01:21:27,048
So play like one tonight.

1170
01:21:35,681 --> 01:21:37,892
Oh, shit.

1171
01:21:40,978 --> 01:21:44,148
When you're getting your pitch,
you're hitting .625, massive.

1172
01:21:44,315 --> 01:21:46,150
You're crushing the ball.

1173
01:21:46,317 --> 01:21:49,195
But when you swing at things...
Your pitch is middle-in.

1174
01:21:49,362 --> 01:21:52,240
When you're swinging low and away,
you're batting. 158.

1175
01:21:52,407 --> 01:21:54,492
Every at bat's
like a hand of blackjack.

1176
01:21:54,659 --> 01:21:56,994
Every card that's dealt,
your odds change.

1177
01:21:57,161 --> 01:22:01,499
So every first-pitch strike, your batting
average goes down about 75 points.

1178
01:22:01,666 --> 01:22:02,834
Seventy-five points.

1179
01:22:03,000 --> 01:22:05,253
He should throw 100 pitches
before the fifth.

1180
01:22:05,420 --> 01:22:07,171
You wanna knock that starter out.

1181
01:22:07,338 --> 01:22:10,842
I want you taking at bats off the 10th
and 11 Th pitcher by the end.

1182
01:22:11,008 --> 01:22:13,428
This is your basic breakdown
of the pitches...

1183
01:22:13,594 --> 01:22:15,805
where you should be hitting them,
why.

1184
01:22:15,972 --> 01:22:19,517
- So you want us to walk more?
- Good question. Yes.

1185
01:22:20,935 --> 01:22:23,020
Mr. Justice.

1186
01:22:23,187 --> 01:22:25,148
- Had a few thoughts.
- Yeah?

1187
01:22:25,314 --> 01:22:27,692
- Yeah.
- Gonna teach me some things?

1188
01:22:28,151 --> 01:22:29,861
Excuse me?

1189
01:22:31,404 --> 01:22:33,698
Never seen a GM talk to players
like that.

1190
01:22:33,865 --> 01:22:36,534
You never seen a GM
who was a player.

1191
01:22:42,832 --> 01:22:45,626
- We got a problem, David?
- No, it's okay.

1192
01:22:45,793 --> 01:22:48,004
I know your routine.

1193
01:22:48,171 --> 01:22:51,424
It's patter. It's for effect.

1194
01:22:52,717 --> 01:22:56,888
But it's for them, all right?
That shit ain't for me.

1195
01:22:57,388 --> 01:22:59,140
Oh, you're special?

1196
01:23:01,559 --> 01:23:06,189
You're paying me 7 million bucks
a year, man, so, yeah...

1197
01:23:06,355 --> 01:23:08,691
maybe I am, a little bit.

1198
01:23:08,858 --> 01:23:11,819
No, man, I ain't paying you 7.

1199
01:23:12,528 --> 01:23:14,405
Yankees are paying half your salary.

1200
01:23:14,572 --> 01:23:17,408
That's what the New York Yankees
think of you.

1201
01:23:18,242 --> 01:23:22,580
They're paying you $3.5 million
to play against them.

1202
01:23:23,873 --> 01:23:26,042
Where you going with this, Billy?

1203
01:23:26,834 --> 01:23:29,170
David, you're 37.

1204
01:23:29,337 --> 01:23:33,090
How about you and I be honest about
what each of us want out of this?

1205
01:23:34,717 --> 01:23:38,095
I wanna milk the last ounce of baseball
you got in you.

1206
01:23:38,262 --> 01:23:40,556
And you wanna stay in the show.

1207
01:23:41,098 --> 01:23:43,059
Let's do that.

1208
01:23:43,935 --> 01:23:46,521
I'm not paying you
for the player you used to be.

1209
01:23:46,687 --> 01:23:49,690
I'm paying you for the player you are
right now.

1210
01:23:49,857 --> 01:23:53,277
You're smart.
You get what we're trying to do here.

1211
01:23:53,444 --> 01:23:56,280
Make an example
for the younger guys.

1212
01:23:56,447 --> 01:23:58,241
Be a leader.

1213
01:23:58,908 --> 01:24:00,576
Can you do that?

1214
01:24:07,667 --> 01:24:10,628
All right. I got you.

1215
01:24:13,089 --> 01:24:14,799
We're cool?

1216
01:24:16,884 --> 01:24:18,344
We're cool.

1217
01:24:23,641 --> 01:24:24,850
Scotty H.

1218
01:24:25,017 --> 01:24:27,853
- Yo, what's up, D.J.?
- Picking machine.

1219
01:24:28,312 --> 01:24:30,731
How you liking first base, man?

1220
01:24:32,024 --> 01:24:35,236
It's coming along. Picking it up.

1221
01:24:35,403 --> 01:24:39,532
You know, tough transition,
but I'm starting to feel better with it.

1222
01:24:39,699 --> 01:24:41,742
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

1223
01:24:41,909 --> 01:24:43,828
What's your biggest fear?

1224
01:24:44,453 --> 01:24:47,164
A baseball being hit
in my general direction.

1225
01:24:49,250 --> 01:24:52,378
That's funny. Seriously, what is it?

1226
01:24:55,840 --> 01:24:58,175
No, seriously, that is.

1227
01:25:08,936 --> 01:25:11,272
Well, hey, good luck with that.

1228
01:25:11,439 --> 01:25:13,608
Be social out there.

1229
01:25:14,525 --> 01:25:17,069
- Social.
- Social. Like a greeter at the Gap.

1230
01:25:17,236 --> 01:25:19,322
Guy steps into your office,
chat him up.

1231
01:25:19,488 --> 01:25:22,158
You're well-read.
You went to school.

1232
01:25:22,325 --> 01:25:24,493
- Yeah.
- Have some fun. Relax.

1233
01:25:24,660 --> 01:25:27,538
Everyone wants to attack.
Quit trying to attack.

1234
01:25:27,705 --> 01:25:30,958
Let the game come to you, man.
There's no clock on this thing.

1235
01:25:31,125 --> 01:25:32,543
This is a war of attrition.

1236
01:25:32,710 --> 01:25:37,131
If I take more, I could even take
a few strikes, but I'll get walked more.

1237
01:25:37,298 --> 01:25:41,052
You get on base, we win.
You don't, we lose.

1238
01:25:41,218 --> 01:25:44,555
And I hate losing, Chavvie. I hate it.

1239
01:25:44,722 --> 01:25:47,308
I hate losing
more than I even wanna win.

1240
01:25:47,475 --> 01:25:48,809
And there's a difference.

1241
01:25:48,976 --> 01:25:50,478
- No bunts.
- Bunts is an out.

1242
01:25:50,645 --> 01:25:53,898
- Even if the third baseman is back?
- No bunting whatsoever.

1243
01:25:54,065 --> 01:25:56,817
If someone bunts on us,
throw it to first.

1244
01:25:56,984 --> 01:25:58,736
Don't be a hero and go to second.

1245
01:25:58,903 --> 01:26:00,321
Let them make the mistakes.

1246
01:26:00,488 --> 01:26:03,407
When your enemy's making mistakes,
don't interrupt them.

1247
01:26:03,574 --> 01:26:06,118
They're giving you an out.
Just giving it to you.

1248
01:26:06,285 --> 01:26:07,578
Take it. Say thank you.

1249
01:26:07,745 --> 01:26:09,747
Another thing. No more stealing.

1250
01:26:09,914 --> 01:26:11,957
That's what I do,
what you pay me to do.

1251
01:26:12,124 --> 01:26:15,086
I pay you to get on first,
not get thrown out at second.

1252
01:26:15,252 --> 01:26:20,216
This is a process.
It's a process, it's a process. Okay?

1253
01:26:32,561 --> 01:26:36,440
<i>Jason takes it, goes to second
for the only out, and the A's get a run.</i>

1254
01:26:38,067 --> 01:26:42,154
<i>Jermaine Dye homers again,
his second in two games.</i>

1255
01:26:43,656 --> 01:26:46,784
<i>And the A's are still hanging in.</i>
<i>We'll get you scores here.</i>

1256
01:26:46,951 --> 01:26:51,414
<i>The A's pull within two
of the Angels for the wild-card chase.</i>

1257
01:26:51,580 --> 01:26:53,749
<i>The Reds have now dropped
five in a row...</i>

1258
01:26:53,916 --> 01:26:57,294
<i>as Oakland beats them
in the beginning of this series 5 to 3.</i>

1259
01:26:57,461 --> 01:26:58,796
<i>Tejada walks.</i>

1260
01:26:58,963 --> 01:27:00,297
<i>Ball four.</i>

1261
01:27:00,464 --> 01:27:03,342
<i>Ball four and Hatteberg walks.</i>

1262
01:27:04,885 --> 01:27:08,389
<i>What is happening in Oakland?
The A's have won seven in a row.</i>

1263
01:27:08,556 --> 01:27:10,808
<i>A lot of excitement.
What a winning streak.</i>

1264
01:27:10,975 --> 01:27:13,811
<i>But how about the calming influence
of Art Howe?</i>

1265
01:27:13,978 --> 01:27:17,606
When you say "your source,"
if it's not me or Peter, they don't know.

1266
01:27:17,773 --> 01:27:19,483
<i>He's managing
an unorthodox team.</i>

1267
01:27:19,650 --> 01:27:21,444
- Right.
<i>- It's not a perfect roster.</i>

1268
01:27:21,610 --> 01:27:24,905
<i>But right now, Art Howe is the reason
this team is winning.</i>

1269
01:27:25,072 --> 01:27:27,658
- <i>He deserves the credit.</i>
- Great, thanks. Bye.

1270
01:27:27,825 --> 01:27:29,368
Did you hear that?

1271
01:27:29,535 --> 01:27:32,496
I heard "seven in a row."
You get the Cleveland matchups?

1272
01:27:32,663 --> 01:27:34,582
Yeah, right here.

1273
01:27:42,339 --> 01:27:43,799
- Voos.
- Billy.

1274
01:27:43,966 --> 01:27:47,219
- That smell is getting worse.
- I'm on it.

1275
01:27:47,970 --> 01:27:50,139
- What are we doing?
- Splitting it in half?

1276
01:27:50,306 --> 01:27:52,141
- Both sides of the plate.
- Got it.

1277
01:27:52,850 --> 01:27:55,019
- Huddy. Mix it up.
- Yes, sir.

1278
01:27:55,186 --> 01:27:57,354
- Trust your slider, yeah?
- Yes, sir.

1279
01:27:57,521 --> 01:27:59,523
You guys quit distracting him.

1280
01:27:59,690 --> 01:28:02,401
You couldn't hit that shit last night
with a paddle.

1281
01:28:02,568 --> 01:28:04,403
You gotta see more pitches.

1282
01:28:04,570 --> 01:28:07,072
- All right, Billy.
- Patience.

1283
01:28:10,868 --> 01:28:12,495
- Hey, David.
- Hey, Billy.

1284
01:28:12,661 --> 01:28:14,038
- Great at bats.
- Thank you.

1285
01:28:14,205 --> 01:28:15,748
- Really quality.
- Thank you.

1286
01:28:15,915 --> 01:28:18,626
<i>Base hit to right field.
Tejada scores.</i>

1287
01:28:18,793 --> 01:28:21,670
<i>Chavez coming in.
The ball gets past Guiel.</i>

1288
01:28:22,588 --> 01:28:26,717
<i>The A's, from 5-nothing down,
now lead 6 to 5.</i>

1289
01:28:36,727 --> 01:28:39,730
<i>The Oakland A's are completely
out of hand at the moment.</i>

1290
01:28:39,897 --> 01:28:42,566
<i>They are an AL-best 17 and 4
this month.</i>

1291
01:28:42,733 --> 01:28:46,529
<i>They also took back-to-back series
at Boston and at New York.</i>

1292
01:28:46,695 --> 01:28:49,323
<i>Remember when they traded
Jeremy Giambi in June...</i>

1293
01:28:49,490 --> 01:28:51,826
<i>and everyone thought
they’d just given up?</i>

1294
01:28:51,992 --> 01:28:54,662
<i>Actually, not so much.</i>

1295
01:28:59,416 --> 01:29:01,252
<i>Suzanne, get Shapiro on the phone.</i>

1296
01:29:01,752 --> 01:29:04,922
- You thinking Rincon?
- His season's done. He's lost faith.

1297
01:29:05,089 --> 01:29:08,092
- I think he's gonna dump him.
- Hard-core.

1298
01:29:08,259 --> 01:29:10,553
Shapiro on 2.

1299
01:29:12,096 --> 01:29:13,889
Mark, Billy. Let's be honest.

1300
01:29:14,056 --> 01:29:17,434
A premier setup man isn't
gonna get you closer to the play-offs.

1301
01:29:17,601 --> 01:29:21,689
<i>- Are you referring to Rincon?</i>
- He's a luxury you can't afford, man.

1302
01:29:21,856 --> 01:29:24,567
<i>And you can?
There's half a million on his contract.</i>

1303
01:29:24,733 --> 01:29:26,777
<i>And we've got
at least one other suitor.</i>

1304
01:29:26,944 --> 01:29:29,655
By "at least one," you mean one.

1305
01:29:29,822 --> 01:29:32,283
- Who is it?
<i>- I'd rather not say.</i>

1306
01:29:32,449 --> 01:29:34,785
- San Francisco.
- San Francisco.

1307
01:29:34,952 --> 01:29:36,453
I'll call you back.

1308
01:29:38,247 --> 01:29:40,416
What do you think we can get
for Magnante?

1309
01:29:40,583 --> 01:29:41,834
Nothing.

1310
01:29:42,751 --> 01:29:45,796
- What's left on Venafro's contract?
- Two seventy-five.

1311
01:29:46,630 --> 01:29:48,424
Suzanne,
get me Sabean on the line.

1312
01:29:48,591 --> 01:29:52,678
Get the Giants interested in Venafro,
Mark's only got one buyer for Rincon.

1313
01:29:52,845 --> 01:29:54,305
- Us.
- On 3.

1314
01:29:56,348 --> 01:29:59,810
Saby-Sabster, it's Billy.
What do you think of Venafro?

1315
01:29:59,977 --> 01:30:02,146
I can let you have him
for almost nothing.

1316
01:30:02,313 --> 01:30:04,899
<i>- Why would you do that?</i>
- Because I'm amazing.

1317
01:30:05,065 --> 01:30:07,067
I want a couple bucks
and a sweetener.

1318
01:30:07,484 --> 01:30:09,320
Throw in, say...

1319
01:30:09,486 --> 01:30:11,655
- Anderson.
- Anderson.

1320
01:30:11,822 --> 01:30:14,783
- <i>I like Anderson.</i>
- No, you don't. Nobody likes him.

1321
01:30:14,950 --> 01:30:17,494
I don't know why I'm doing this.
But let's do it.

1322
01:30:17,661 --> 01:30:20,581
Venafro for Michaelson. Anderson.
I don't know his name.

1323
01:30:20,748 --> 01:30:23,626
- <i>I'll think about it.</i>
- Think about it and call me back.

1324
01:30:24,168 --> 01:30:26,170
Get Shapiro on.

1325
01:30:34,094 --> 01:30:36,347
Shapiro's on 2.

1326
01:30:38,390 --> 01:30:40,351
- Mark.
- <i>You can't afford him, Billy.</i>

1327
01:30:40,517 --> 01:30:41,602
You sure about that?

1328
01:30:41,769 --> 01:30:44,980
I get the impression
the market for Rincon is softening.

1329
01:30:45,147 --> 01:30:47,942
I could be wrong,
but I'd call whoever's interested...

1330
01:30:48,108 --> 01:30:51,612
and see if they're still interested.
Call me back.

1331
01:30:52,488 --> 01:30:55,866
- What about the Mets for Venafro?
- You offered him to the Giants.

1332
01:30:56,033 --> 01:30:57,701
Suzanne, Steve Phillips.

1333
01:30:57,868 --> 01:31:02,706
Between Bonds, Kent, Nen, Snow,
San Francisco's never gonna do it.

1334
01:31:03,123 --> 01:31:06,877
- Totally agree.
- We just need them to cool on Rincon.

1335
01:31:07,044 --> 01:31:10,172
- Phillips on 2.
- Steve-o, it's Billy.

1336
01:31:10,339 --> 01:31:14,051
I hear you're looking for a reliever.
I can give you Venafro.

1337
01:31:14,218 --> 01:31:16,720
- I can make it quick and easy.
<i>- What's the angle?</i>

1338
01:31:16,887 --> 01:31:19,890
- No angle.
<i>- Who am I getting fleeced for?</i>

1339
01:31:20,557 --> 01:31:23,936
- Hang on a sec.
- Bennett, maybe?

1340
01:31:24,103 --> 01:31:25,479
- How old?
- Twenty-six.

1341
01:31:25,646 --> 01:31:27,731
Twenty-six, Double-A? Forget it.

1342
01:31:27,898 --> 01:31:29,984
Duncan, no.

1343
01:31:31,777 --> 01:31:33,529
No. Furbush, no.

1344
01:31:36,198 --> 01:31:39,910
Eckerton? Eckerton? Eckerton.

1345
01:31:41,036 --> 01:31:42,997
- Eckerton.
<i>- Eckerton? I like Eckerton.</i>

1346
01:31:43,163 --> 01:31:46,417
- You don't even know who Eckerton is.
<i>- ls Venafro hurt?</i>

1347
01:31:46,583 --> 01:31:49,920
No, he's fine, he's fine.
It's just an issue for us.

1348
01:31:50,087 --> 01:31:52,756
- <i>Last couple times, he got hammered.</i>
- Not his fault.

1349
01:31:52,923 --> 01:31:55,092
- That was us. We misused him.
- It's Steve.

1350
01:31:55,259 --> 01:31:57,261
- I'm almost done.
- Steve Schott.

1351
01:31:57,678 --> 01:32:00,639
Look, Steve-o,
let me be straight with you.

1352
01:32:00,806 --> 01:32:03,600
Here's the deal.
I'm getting Rincon. It's a done deal.

1353
01:32:03,767 --> 01:32:06,854
- <i>I heard the Giants-</i>-
- Giants want Venafro for Michaelson.

1354
01:32:07,021 --> 01:32:08,939
- Anderson.
- I'd rather deal with you.

1355
01:32:09,106 --> 01:32:12,109
You can give me Eckerton
and $225,000 in cash...

1356
01:32:12,276 --> 01:32:14,319
and the Giants can't.

1357
01:32:15,154 --> 01:32:17,197
- <i>I'll think about it.</i>
- Think about it.

1358
01:32:17,364 --> 01:32:19,742
But whoever calls me back first
gets Venafro.

1359
01:32:22,161 --> 01:32:23,370
Schott hung up.

1360
01:32:24,830 --> 01:32:28,125
Oh, I want this one.

1361
01:32:36,133 --> 01:32:38,469
Why isn't anybody calling?

1362
01:32:41,263 --> 01:32:43,474
Shapiro's on 2.

1363
01:32:44,850 --> 01:32:46,268
Yeah?

1364
01:32:50,439 --> 01:32:53,067
Okay, let me talk to my owner.
I'll call you back.

1365
01:32:53,233 --> 01:32:55,944
- Get Steve on the phone.
- Schott or Phillips?

1366
01:32:56,111 --> 01:32:58,989
Why would we call Phillips?
Phillips has gotta call us.

1367
01:33:02,826 --> 01:33:04,578
Tell him I'm on the other line.

1368
01:33:08,332 --> 01:33:12,002
Hi, Mr. Schott, it's Peter Brand.
I apologize for putting you on hold.

1369
01:33:12,169 --> 01:33:16,965
- Billy asked me to call you back.
- Tell him we want 225,000 for Rincon.

1370
01:33:17,132 --> 01:33:22,179
Billy says he needs $225,000
for Ricardo Rincon.

1371
01:33:22,721 --> 01:33:24,348
Please.

1372
01:33:25,849 --> 01:33:29,144
Yes, I added the "please" at the end.

1373
01:33:30,521 --> 01:33:33,774
Okay. Let me...
Hold on one second, please.

1374
01:33:34,566 --> 01:33:36,568
Tell him I'll pay for him.

1375
01:33:36,735 --> 01:33:41,073
But when I sell him back for twice the
amount next year, I keep the money.

1376
01:33:43,033 --> 01:33:46,036
Okay, so Billy says
he'll pay for Rincon himself.

1377
01:33:46,203 --> 01:33:50,499
But when he sells him for more money
next year, he's keeping the profit.

